I am noting for you that those who compete with MS on its own platform are doing
anything but holding their own.  Please name for me one company and product 
in direct competition with MS on their windows platform that is consistently
holding on to their market share, not losing ground to an MS product.  

The point is that MS Windows is not a level playing field for anyone in 
a direct competition with a product from MS.

Dont put words into my mouth, I am *NOT* claiming "they should run to OS/2 
and be *saved*".  I am noting that at the present time, competition with 
microsoft is a losing proposition.  I question out loud as to whether or not
it is due to MS sharing info between OS and development that other people dont
have, or due to their incredible aptitude at marketing.  Apart from Excel, I
have doubts that quality of product has anything whatsoever to do with their
success.

What I *DO* advocate is taking a multiplatform approach, in such a way that
if you lose your shirt in MSes platforms, you can still operate on other 
platforms such as Unix, OS/2, VMS, etc.  Using tools like XVT or other 
multiplatform dev tools makes this job not very difficult in general, though
you do have to code more carefully.

However, you should note that WordPerfect is being effectively dismantled 
inside of Novell.  WordPerfect competes directly with MS word... but they
have not had much success in the market as of late.  Lotus is in serious 
trouble in the Windows market.  They know it. 

Borland is no longer a serious competitor to MS in productivity products.  MS
has cornered the market.  The question is, did they do it fairly or not?

Well, worse than that, any company in direct competition with MS should seriously
consider the consequences of their actions...  MS takes no prisoners, and has
not yet (to my knowledge) lost any battles.

