>numerous products that overlap in terms of power and capability.  DB2 competes

The YMP I used to use overlaps in terms of power and capability the little 
386 box on my desk....  Sorry, "overlaps" of "power and capability" are quite
subjective, and quite irrelevant.  As I noted above, you use the right tool for
the job.  Period.  Paradox cant easily run a high speed transaction 
processing system with data distribution, fault tolerance, etc.  Likewise 
using oracle to manage your 50 to 100 person client contact database is more 
than overkill.  Neither tool is scoped properly for the aforementioned task.  

I wouldnt want to run my molecular dynamics on the little 386 in my office,
though I can do this if needed.  The YMP does a much better job.  Likewise,
paradox does a great job at what it is used for, and the high end is open
for other products to fill.  (This is not meant to disparage paradox, as it is
a good database system, that I use for my clients onsite).  However, when you 
have 10**8 data points per year that you need to archive, paradox doesnt
cut the mustard.  Here DB2, Oracle or Ingress will shine.  You use the right 
tool for the job.  

Paradox competes with Oracle, DB2, etc, in much the same way that my car
is in competition with a large truck.  Both will allow me to transport
things around.  My car has a small carrying capacity, and is good for
short quick hauls, like taking me to my office.  The truck on the otherhand 
has the advantage of much larger carrying capacity, and can haul larger loads
about.  I would not want to use the car to move myself from one house
to another, and I wouldnt want to use the truck for my day to day activities.

In the sense that both are competing for funds as they are both in the
transportation market, sure there is "competition" there.  However, the 
systems are targetted towards different segments of the market...  They 
are not in DIRECT competition.

That is the difference between paradox and DB2 etc.  THey are not in 
direct competition.  Many unix databases use techniques for file
management not found in paradox.   They do this to speed the flow of
information.  This isbecause they handle incredible volumes of info.
However, paradox uses techniques that the unix boxes cant use to speed
up its processing.  They are in different market segments, and they
are trying their best to make sure that they do the best job at what
they are supposed to do.  Direct competition?  No.  


